{"title_page": "Anne Klein", "text_new": "{{short description|American fashion designer}}{{Infobox fashion designer\n| name               = Anne Klein\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| alt                = Anne Klein\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Hannah Golofsky<ref name=\"encyclopedia1923\">{{cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/women/dictionaries-thesauruses-pictures-and-press-releases/klein-anne-1923-1974 |title=Klein, Anne (1923\u20131974) |publisher=encyclopedia.com |date=|accessdate=2018-05-24}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1923|8|3}}<ref name=\"encyclopedia1923\"/>\n| birth_place        = [[Brooklyn]], New York, U.S.<ref name=\"encyclopedia1923\"/>\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|1974|3|19|1923|8|3}}<ref name=\"encyclopedia1923\"/>\n| death_place        = New York City, U.S.\n| other_names        = Hannah Golofski\n| education          = [[Traphagen School of Fashion]]<ref name=\"SterlacciArbuckle2017\">{{cite book|author1=[[Francesca Sterlacci]]|author2=Joanne Arbuckle|title=Historical Dictionary of the Fashion Industry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jycnDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA264|date=30 June 2017|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=978-1-4422-3909-8|pages=264\u2013}}</ref>\n| alma_mater         = \n| spouse             = Ben Klein <br> Matthew Rubenstein\n| label_name         = Anne Klein & Co\n| significant_design = \n}}\n \n{{otherpeople}}\n\n'''Anne Klein''' (August 3, 1923 &ndash; March 19, 1974) was an American fashion designer and business woman, the founder and namesake of Anne Klein & Company.<ref name=\"encyclopedia1923\"/> She co-founded Anne Klein & Company in 1968 with Gunther Oppenheim, and within ten years her designs were being sold in over 750 department stores and boutiques in the USA.<ref> Cassavechia, Jamie (July 17, 2019).[https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20190717005129/en/WHP-Global-Launches-New-Brand-Management-Platform \"WHP Global Launches as New Brand Management Platform with $200 Million Equity Fund Commitment from Oaktree\"]''.[[Business Wire]]''</ref>\n\nHer design career began in 1937 when she was awarded a scholarship to attend the Traphagen School of Fashion,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fitnyc.edu/museum/exhibitions/traphagen-school.php|title=The Traphagen School: Fostering American Fashion|last=|first=|date=|website=Fashion Institute of Technology (FIT)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref> which led to her first job as a sketcher for dress firms on 7th Avenue.\n\nIn 1948 she married clothing manufacturer Ben Klein, with whom she launched the Junior Sophisticates clothing line <ref name=\"SterlacciArbuckle2017\" />. Junior Sophisticates offered styles to younger women with smaller figures. Anne Klein was the principal designer at Junior Sophisticates until 1960, when her marriage ended. In 1963, she married her second husband, Matthew \"Chip\" Rubenstein, and in 1968, they founded Anne Klein & Company at 39th Street. She also opened Anne Klein Studio at 57th Street.\n<ref>{{cite book |title=Historical Dictionary of the Fashion Industry |date=June 30, 2017 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers |isbn=9781442239098 |page=264 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Historical_Dictionary_of_the_Fashion_Ind/jycnDwAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=anne+klein+freelance+design&pg=PA264&printsec=frontcover) |accessdate=7 March 2020 |ref=Historical Dictionary Fashion Industry}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in 1954 with the Mademoiselle Merit Award, Anne Klein won numerous fashion awards and gained international recognition.\n\nIn 1973, she was the only woman invited to participate in a fashion show consisting of five American and five French designers, intended to raise money for renovations at Versailles <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/fashion/article/30483/1/the-70s-fashion-show-pitting-america-against-france-battle-of-versailles |title=The secret history of fashion\u2019s ultimate showdown &#124; Dazed |publisher=Dazeddigital.com |date=2016-03-23 |accessdate=2018-05-24}}</ref><ref name=\"fashion\" /><ref name=\"Times-later-feature\">{{cite news |last1=Morris |first1=Bernadine \n|title=Review/Design; When America Stole the Runway From Paris Couture|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/09/10/arts/review-design-when-america-stole-the-runway-from-paris-couture.html|website=The New York Times|date= 10 September 1993 |accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref> \n\n== Early life and education ==\n\n\nAnne Klein was born August 3, 1923 in Brooklyn, New York, as Hannah Golofski <ref name=\"encyclopedia1923\" />.  Her father, Morris Golofski, owned a fleet of taxicabs; her mother was Esther Golofski. <ref>Green, David B.(February 8, 2015).[https://www.haaretz.com/jewish/.premium-this-day-anne-klein-is-born-1.5382143 \"This Day in Jewish History: Hannah Golofski Is Born, Will Change Her Name and Women's Fashion\"]''.[[Haaretz]]''</ref> She was known to say that she changed her name from Hannah to Anne because it was more aesthetically pleasing.\n\nIt was while studying art at Girls' Commercial High School (now known as [[Prospect Heights High School]]) that she discovered her talent for design. Within a year\u2019s time, she was employed at her first job in the garment industry with Varden Petites. There, she worked to redesign the firm's collection and introduced a new style of ready-to-wear clothing for young, smaller figured women that would come to be known as \"Junior Miss\" <ref name=\"SterlacciArbuckle2017\" />.\n\nIn 1937 she was awarded a scholarship to attend the [[Traphagen School of Fashion]] which led to her first job as a sketcher for dress firms on 7th Avenue. She started her fashion career while at the Traphagen School of Fashion in New York City, studying between 1937 and 1938.<ref name=\"fashion\">{{cite web|url=http://www.famousfashiondesigners.org/anne-klein |title=Anne Klein &#124; Fashion Designer Biography |publisher=Famousfashiondesigners.org |date=2017-11-22 |accessdate=2018-05-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fitnyc.edu/museum/exhibitions/traphagen-school.php|title=The Traphagen School: Fostering American Fashion|last=|first=|date=|website=Fashion Institute of Technology (FIT)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref>.\n\n==Fashion Career 1940s and 1950s==\n\n\nIn 1940, Anne Klein began making a name for herself as a designer. She first began designing for Maurice Rentner at his business, Maurice Rentner, Inc., which produced ready-to-wear designs for men and women. <ref>Stewart,Katherin [https://www.martelnyc.com/womenswear-3/anne-klein-hannah-golofsky.html \"Anne Klein Hannah Golofsky\"]''</ref>\n\nIn 1944, Anne Klein joined Bonnie Cashin and Claire McCardell to form a female design trio who laid the foundations of American sportswear.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pundir |first1=Nirupama |title=Fashion Technology: Today and Tomorrow |date=2007 |publisher=Mittal Publications |isbn=978-81-8324-203-5 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Fashion_Technology/CON2O1zy3rAC?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq= |language=en}}</ref> \n\nIn 1948 she married clothing manufacturer Ben Klein and they launched the Junior Sophisticates label. Junior Sophisticates offered elegant styles to younger women with smaller figures. Anne Klein was the principal designer at Junior Sophisticates until 1960, when her marriage ended <ref name=\"SterlacciArbuckle2017\" />. It was during this time of ready-to-wear fashion, \"modern\" designs for women, and an increase in the number of women in the workplace that Klein was one of the first to introduce, and to become known for, \"separates\": individual pieces which work together as a whole, as opposed to dresses.\n\nAbout this time she began winning awards in the fashion industry including:\n\n1954 she was awarded the Mademoiselle Merit Award. <ref name=\"encyclopedia2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/fashion/news-wires-white-papers-and-books/klein-anne |title=Klein, Anne |publisher=encyclopedia.com |date=|accessdate=2018-05-24}}</ref>\n\n1954 she was awarded the [[Coty Award|Coty]] American Fashion Critics Award.<ref name=\"encyclopedia2\"/>\n\n1959 she was awarded the Neiman-Marcus Fashion Award for the first time, leading to international recognition as a fashion designer. <ref name=\"encyclopedia2\"/><ref name=\"SterlacciArbuckle2017\"/>\n\n== Fashion Career 1960s and 1970s ==\n\nIn 1960 her marriage to Ben Klein ended, as did her association with Junior Sophisticates. <ref name=\"SterlacciArbuckle2017\" />\n\nDuring the early 1960s, after her divorce from Ben Klein, she kept the name Klein and worked as a freelance designer, reinvigorating well-known but faltering lines such as Pierre Cardin coats and Evan-Picone. <ref>{{cite book |title=Historical Dictionary of the Fashion Industry |date=June 30, 2017 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers |isbn=9781442239098 |page=264 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Historical_Dictionary_of_the_Fashion_Ind/jycnDwAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=anne+klein+freelance+design&pg=PA264&printsec=frontcover) |accessdate=7 March 2020 |ref=Historical Dictionary Fashion Industry}}</ref>\n\nThis freelance work helped to fund her 1963 opening of Anne Klein Studio on 57th Street. Also in 1963 she married a second time to Matthew \"Chip\" Rubenstein. <ref>Cummings, Judith (March 20, 1974).[https://www.nytimes.com/1974/03/20/archives/anne-klein-dead-designer-was-51-influential-in-styling-casual-but.html \"ONE MIN DEAD; DESIGNER WAS 51; Influential in Styling Casual but Elegant Clothing\"]''.[[New York Times]]''</ref>\n\nIn 1961 she was one of a select group to win the American Creativity Award. (<ref>Campbell, Nicky (November 16, 2018).[https://cfda.com/news/the-enduring-legacy-of-anne-klein \"The Enduring Legacy of Anne Klein\"]''.[[CFDA]]''</ref>\n\nIn 1964 she was awarded the Lord & Taylor Rose Award for independent thinking, an award first given to Albert Einstein. <ref name=\"encyclopedia2\"/>\n\nIn 1968, she established the Anne Klein & Company label as director and co-owner with her husband, on 39th Street. The label was opened in collaboration with investor Gunther Oppenheim, a fashion industry stalwart <ref name=\"fashion\">{{cite web|url=http://www.famousfashiondesigners.org/anne-klein |title=Anne Klein &#124; Fashion Designer Biography |publisher=Famousfashiondesigners.org |date=2017-11-22 |accessdate=2018-05-24}}</ref>. The next ten years saw an expansion of the business, with over 750 department stores and boutiques in America selling her designs. <ref> Cassavechia, Jamie (July 17, 2019).[https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20190717005129/en/WHP-Global-Launches-New-Brand-Management-Platform \"WHP Global Launches as New Brand Management Platform with $200 Million Equity Fund Commitment from Oaktree\"]''.[[Business Wire]]''</ref>\n\nIn 1969 she was awarded the Neiman-Marcus Fashion Award; she was, later, the first designer to win the award for a second time.<ref name=\"encyclopedia2\"/><ref name=\"SterlacciArbuckle2017\"/>\n\nIn 1970, Klein opened the first designer shop-in-shop boutique, \"Anne Klein Corner\" in Saks Fifth Avenue, New York. That year, she was awarded the [[Coty Award|Coty]] American Fashion Critics Award, which she would win again. A year later, in 1971, she was named to the Coty Fashion Hall of Fame<ref name=\"SterlacciArbuckle2017\"/>. The 8th designer to be so inducted in 28 years. \n\n1973 she was included as one of five designers invited to show at the legendary Battle of Versailles design competition. The competition served to raise money for renovations at Versailles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/fashion/article/30483/1/the-70s-fashion-show-pitting-america-against-france-battle-of-versailles |title=The secret history of fashion\u2019s ultimate showdown &#124; Dazed |publisher=Dazeddigital.com |date=2016-03-23 |accessdate=2018-05-24}}</ref><ref name=\"fashion\" /><ref name=\"Times-later-feature\">{{cite news |last1=Morris |first1=Bernadine \n|title=Review/Design; When America Stole the Runway From Paris Couture|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/09/10/arts/review-design-when-america-stole-the-runway-from-paris-couture.html|website=The New York Times|date= 10 September 1993 |accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\n\nMarch 19, 1974 Anne Klein died at the age of 51 of breast cancer at Mount Sinai Hospital, New York, NY . <ref>Morris, Bernadine (March 22, 1974).[https://www.nytimes.com/1974/03/22/archives/fashions-family-gathers-to-mourn-and-honoranne-klein.html \"Fashion's Family Gathers to Mourn and Honor Anne Klein\"]''.[[The New York Times]]''</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* 1954 \u2013 Mademoiselle Merit Award<ref name=\"encyclopedia2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/fashion/news-wires-white-papers-and-books/klein-anne |title=Klein, Anne |publisher=encyclopedia.com |date=|accessdate=2018-05-24}}</ref>\n* 1955, 1969, 1971 \u2013 [[Coty Award|Coty]] American Fashion Critics Award<ref name=\"encyclopedia2\"/>\n* 1959, 1969 \u2013 [[Neiman Marcus]] Award (Klein was the first designer to receive this award twice)<ref name=\"encyclopedia2\"/><ref name=\"SterlacciArbuckle2017\"/>\n* 1964 \u2013 [[Lord & Taylor]] Award<ref name=\"encyclopedia2\"/>\n* 1965 \u2013 National Cotton Council Award<ref name=\"encyclopedia2\"/>\n* 1971 \u2013 Induction into the [[Coty Award|Coty]] Fashion Hall of Fame<ref name=\"SterlacciArbuckle2017\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{fashiondesigner|id=anne-klein}}\n*[http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/42547 American Ingenuity: Sportswear 1930s-1970s], an exhibition catalog from The Metropolitan Museum of Art Libraries (fully available online as PDF), which contains material on Anne Klein (see index)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{American sportswear}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Klein, Anne}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:1974 deaths]]\n[[Category:American fashion designers]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:Deaths from breast cancer]]\n[[Category:Jewish fashion designers]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Traphagen School of Fashion alumni]]\n[[Category:Women inventors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American fashion designer}}{{Infobox fashion designer\n| name               = Anne Klein\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| alt                = Anne Klein\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Hannah Golofsky<ref name=\"encyclopedia1923\">{{cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/women/dictionaries-thesauruses-pictures-and-press-releases/klein-anne-1923-1974 |title=Klein, Anne (1923\u20131974) |publisher=encyclopedia.com |date=|accessdate=2018-05-24}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1923|8|3}}<ref name=\"encyclopedia1923\"/>\n| birth_place        = [[Brooklyn]], New York, U.S.<ref name=\"encyclopedia1923\"/>\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|1974|3|19|1923|8|3}}<ref name=\"encyclopedia1923\"/>\n| death_place        = New York City, U.S.\n| other_names        = Hannah Golofski\n| education          = [[Traphagen School of Fashion]]<ref name=\"SterlacciArbuckle2017\">{{cite book|author1=[[Francesca Sterlacci]]|author2=Joanne Arbuckle|title=Historical Dictionary of the Fashion Industry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jycnDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA264|date=30 June 2017|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=978-1-4422-3909-8|pages=264\u2013}}</ref>\n| alma_mater         = \n| spouse             = Ben Klein <br> Matthew Rubenstein\n| label_name         = Anne Klein & Co\n| significant_design = \n}}\n \n{{otherpeople}}\n\n'''Anne Klein''' (August 3, 1923 &ndash; March 19, 1974) was an American fashion designer and business woman, the founder and namesake of Anne Klein & Company.<ref name=\"encyclopedia1923\"/> She co-founded Anne Klein & Company in 1968 with Gunther Oppenheim, and within ten years her designs were being sold in over